T1  - Why markets should not necessarily reduce the tick size
AU  - Bourghelle, David
AU  - Declerck, Fany
JO  - Journal of Banking & Finance
VL  - 28
IS  - 2
SP  - 373
EP  - 398
PY  - 2004
DA  - 2004/02/01/
T2  - Financial Services: Global Perspectives
SN  - 0378-4266
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/S0378-4266(03)00136-5
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0378426603001365
KW  - Tick size
KW  - Liquidity supply
KW  - Spread
KW  - Market depth
KW  - Order exposure
AB  - This paper studies the consequences of a tick size change on the Paris Bourse thus providing a natural experiment on an order-driven market. The change raised the tick size for some stocks and lowered it for other. In contrast with US exchanges results, this generated neither a reduction in liquidity provision for large trades nor a change in the spread. Based on this paper and on US results, it appears an increasing but convex relationship between the relative tick size and the relative spread. Thus, it implies that a new pricing grid does not necessarily lead to change execution costs but it changes the level of transparency in the liquidity supply.
