T1  - The integration of bank syndicated loan and junk bond markets
AU  - Thomas, Hugh
AU  - Wang, Zhiqiang
JO  - Journal of Banking & Finance
VL  - 28
IS  - 2
SP  - 299
EP  - 329
PY  - 2004
DA  - 2004/02/01/
T2  - Financial Services: Global Perspectives
SN  - 0378-4266
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/j.jbankfin.2003.01.001
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0378426603001924
KW  - Syndicated loans
KW  - Junk bonds
KW  - Disintermediation
KW  - Credit spreads
KW  - Bank loan pricing
KW  - Bank liquidity
KW  - Special role of banks
KW  - High yield bonds
KW  - Highly leveraged transactions
AB  - This paper hypothesizes that the special role of banks as corporate quasi-insiders has been changing due to developments in informational, legal and institutional infrastructures of syndicated loan markets. We investigate the integration of intermediated and disintermediated financial markets through highly leveraged transaction (HLT) syndicated loans during the 1990s. We demonstrate that, with the emergence of traded HLT syndicated loans as an alternative high-yield asset to high-yield bonds, market integration has dramatically increased. Taking the late 1980s and 1990s together, different factors explain the movement of credit spreads of the two markets. HLT loan market’s spreads are strongly affected by bank liquidity. Bank liquidity’s effect on HLT loan spreads disappears after 1993. From 1994–1999, junk bond market liquidity factors affect bank loan pricing. We interpret these changes as evidence of the erosion of bank specialness.
ER  - 

